Definition:Abelian Group:
An '''abelian group''' is a group $G$ where:
: $\forall a, b \in G: a b = b a$

That is, every element in $G$ commutes with every other element in $G$.







An '''abelian group''' is a group $G$ {{iff}}:
: $G = \map Z G$
where $\map Z G$ is the center of $G$.







When discussing abelian groups, it is customary to use additive notation, where:

:$x + y$ is used to indicate the result of the operation $+$ on $x$ and $y$.

:$e$ or $0$ is used for the identity element. Note that in this context, $0$ is '''not''' a zero element.

:$-x$ is used for the inverse element.

:$n x$ is used to indicate the $n$th power of $x$.







Under this regime, the group axioms read:

{{begin-axiom}}
{{axiom | n = \text G 0
        | lc= Closure
        | q = \forall x, y \in G
        | m = x + y \in G
}}
{{axiom | n = \text G 1
        | lc= Associativity
        | q = \forall x, y, z \in G
        | m = x + \paren {y + z} = \paren {x + y} + z
}}
{{axiom | n = \text G 2
        | lc= Identity
        | q = \exists 0 \in G: \forall x \in G
        | m = 0 + x = x = x + 0
}}
{{axiom | n = \text G 3
        | lc= Inverse
        | q = \forall x \in G: \exists \paren {-x}\in G
        | m = x + \paren {-x} = 0 = \paren {-x} + x
}}
{{axiom | n = \text C
        | lc= Commutativity
        | q = \forall x, y \in G
        | m = x + y = y + x
}}
{{end-axiom}}


This notation gains in importance and usefulness when discussing rings.

Definition:Composition of Mappings:
Let $S_1$, $S_2$ and $S_3$ be sets.

Let $f_1: S_1 \to S_2$ and $f_2: S_2 \to S_3$ be mappings such that the domain of $f_2$ is the same set as the codomain of $f_1$.







The '''composite mapping''' $f_2 \circ f_1$ is defined as:

:$\forall x \in S_1: \map {\paren {f_2 \circ f_1} } x := \map {f_2} {\map {f_1} x}$







The '''composite of $f_1$ and $f_2$''' is defined and denoted as:

:$f_2 \circ f_1 := \set {\tuple {x, z} \in S_1 \times S_3: \tuple {\map {f_1} x, z} \in f_2}$







The '''composite of $f_1$ and $f_2$''' is defined and denoted as:

:$f_2 \circ f_1 := \set {\tuple {x, z} \in S_1 \times S_3: \exists y \in S_2: \map {f_1} x = y \land \map {f_2} y = z}$


:850px






